We need to determine how much tax liability (output tax) accumulates that has not yet been “paid” – that is, the “Increase (Decrease) in Tax Payable” item for the cash‐flow statement. In our transaction data only the sale entries include a number in the “tax_amount” column. One way to “solve” the task is to sum all the tax_amount values appearing on the Sale transactions. (Other types – purchases, expenses, interest, fixed asset acquisitions – do not show any “tax” amounts so we assume there is no “input tax” that will reduce the liability.)

Below you can see a step–by–step process:

1. Identify each row (by type “Sale”) that carries a non‐blank “tax_amount”. For example, one sale row might be:
  Sale20240102003 with tax_amount = 11,248.06.
2. In our data there are many “Sale” rows. (In our table the rows are, in order, for example: Sale20240102003, Sale20240103005, Sale20240103006, Sale20240104007, Sale20240104008, Sale20240105009, Sale20240106011, … etc.)
